column168: Description Of Events

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING, ONE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT IN THE HALF-WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE AND ONE-HALF PINTS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG A BROOM AND SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO ONE, EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL OVERPACK WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO DUNNAGE.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING, NO SHROUDING WAS PLACED BETWEEN THE DRUMS, CAUSING THE DRUMS TO RUB TOGETHER AND WORE A HOLE IN THE DRUM.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PLACED THE AFFECTED DUNNAGE INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON THE DOCK, PRIOR TO BEING LOADED, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED ON A PALLET.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE PALLET.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE BUNG WAS REPLACED AND THE DRUM WAS FORWARDED.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG AND DAMP ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LOOSE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING NINE, SIXTY-FOUR OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS DISCOVEREDAT THE AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ALL FOUR JUGS WERE LEAKING. APPROXIMATELY HALF A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG AND POLY ABSORBENT TOWELS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, ONE THIRTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL THREE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORT ED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ALL FOUR JUGS WERE LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY THREE AND HALF GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG AND POLY ABSORBENT TOWELS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, ONE THIRTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL THREE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING 2500 POUND STEEL TOTE BIN WAS DISCOVERED ABOUT HALFWAY INTO THETRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINEDINSIDE TH TRAILER. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO OVER-FILLING; THE VENT WAS PLUGGEDAND DUE TO A PRESSURE BUILD-UP, FREE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE SEAL OF THE LID.THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING TYVEK SUITS, GOGGLES,GLOVES, AND ABSORBENT TOWELS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVEGALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.THE TOTE WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. NOINJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED BECAUSE OF A LOAD SHIFT DUE TO AN EMERGENCY ROAD MANEUVER TO AVOID AN ACCIDENT.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL OFF-LOADED CONTENTS INTO NEW TRAILER AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID INTO AN OVERPACK CONTAINER.  SIX DRUMS OF SPENT ABSORBENT AND SOIL FROM THE CLEAN-UP WAS GENERATED.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS THEN PLACED INTO TRAILER SO THEY COULD TRANSPORT IT TO THE NEARBY BRENNTAG FACILITY TO FINISH THE TRAILER DECON BY BRENNTAG PERSONNEL.
1 BOX OF 6, WITH 1 BROKEN, HIT BY PIEDMANT PLASTICS FREIGHT WHEN UNLOADING. BOX BOTTLES WERE IN FELL APART.
3 DRUMS LEAKING AROUND CAPS, CONSIGNEE RECEIVED, SAID THIS WAS PROBABLY NOT SCREWED DOWN GOOD & SPLASHED UP IN TRANSIT
3 BAGS WERE TURN WHEN SOMETHING WAS PUSHED INTO IT WHEN LOADED AT ORIGIN TERMINAL.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED IF THE BAGS HAD BEEN WRAPPED WITH CARDBOARD DUNNAGE.
DRIVER NOTED 3 DENTED 100 GALLON DRUMS DENTED ON TOP AROUND LID- 1 DRUM LID DENTED HAS 2 TABLESPOONS OF PRODUCT AROUND LID.
BX CRUSHED DURING LOADING- CAUSING ONE CONTAINER TO CRUSH IN @ TOP &  LEAK @ BOTTOM- APPROX LOSS 2 OZ.

1 DRUM WAS CUT BY ANOTHER PALLET WHEN THE STRIPPER ROLLED IT OUT OF HIS WAY.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED BY SIMPLY BEING MORE CAREFUL, OR MOVING THE DRUM TO DESTINATION RATHER THAN MOVING IT OUT OF THE WAY.

ON MARCH 12, 2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 0825 HOURS, A RAILWAY TANK CAR UTLX 71138, LOADED WITH CORROSIVE LIQUIDS N.O.S. (SODIUM SULFIDE SOLUTIONS SPENT, CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE) 8, UN1760, PG II WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT THE KANSAS CIYT SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) LATANIER, LOUISIANA YARD.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO THE SITE REPORTING A MISSING MANWAY GASKET.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONDER INSTALLED A NEW MANWAY GASKET AND WRENCH TIGHTENED THE VALVES, THUS CORRECTING THE RELEASE. THE AREA AND TANK CAR JACKET WERE CLEANED, AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DURING THE PRELOAD AT OUR UPS CENTER JUST AS WE WERE ABOUT TO FRESH DUE FIRST FEEDER.  ONE OF MY CO-WORKERS SAW A LEAKING HAZARDOUS PACKAGE.  WE STOPPED THE BELT AND BOT EVERYONE OUT OF THE GENERAL AREA.  I SUITED UP AND TOOK THE PARCEL TO THE DMP AREA.  I USED THE DECISION TREE TO THE PROCESS. AFTER THE PRELOAD I FOLLOWED UPS PROCEDURES TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THERE WAS NO LIQUID LOSSED THE BUILDING.  THE PACKAGE WAS A LITTLE WET.  THE SPILL WAS DUE TO LOOSE CAPS.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: THERE WAS ANOTHER PALLET WAS STACKED ON TOP OF THIS FREIGHT.  THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE USED AROUND OR ON TOP THIS FREIGHT TO PROTECT THE BAGS FROM ANY TYPE OF DAMAGE.

column168: WE RECEIVED ONE CARTON WITH ONE 4 GAL PAIL INSIDE.  THE CARTON WAS LEAKING FROM ONE CORNER.  WHEN WE OPENED TO CHECK THE FREIGHT, WE NOTICED THAT THE PAIL WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE TOP OF THE PAIL WAS LOOSE, THAT IS WHERE IT WAS LEAKING FROM.  THE CARTON WAS OK, IT WAS NOT CRUSHED OR TORN.

column62: Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: PRODUCT WAS LOADED ON TOP OF A LOAD DECK WITHOUT PROPER BRACING.  OTHER FREIGHT FELL INTO SHIPMENT CAUSING BAGS TO FALL TO TRAILER FLOOR CAUSING SPILL.  WHEN SPILL WAS DISCOVERED, ALL PERSONS IN AREA OF SPILL WERE MOVED AWAY AND TRAILER DOOR CLOSED.  CHEMTREC AND CON-WAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED SO WE COULD DETERMINE THE PROPER PROCEDURES TO CLEAN SPILL.  WHEN PROPER PROCEDURES FOR CLEAN UP WERE KNOWN, WE PROCEEDED TO SALVAGE AND CONTAIN THE SPILLED PRODUCT.
DRIVER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT IN FRONT OF PAIL AND FORKS STRUCK PAIL.

column168: FORKLIFT MISHANDLING WAS THE DIRECT CAUSE OF THE SPILL.  DSR DID NOT LOOK BACK WHEN REVERSING AND PUNCTURED THE BAGS.

column26: OLDWATER WORKS RD P O BOX 194
column168: A LOAD OF 80 DRUMS OF FINAL ETCH 5 WAS RECEIVED ON 2/13/04.  ON 3/3/04 AT ABOUT 3:45PM IT WAS NOTICED THAT A DRUM WAS LEAKING ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  THE SPILL WAS INVESTIGATED AND CONTAINED.  THE DRUM APPEARED TO BE LEAKING POSSIBLY FROM A SEAM AT THE BOTTOM.  THE LEAK WAS VERY SLOW AND APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING FOR SOME TIME, POSSIBLY EVEN DURING TRANSPORTATION.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP.  IN THE FUTURE WE WILL MORE CAREFULLY INSPECT SHIPMENTS OF THIS NATURE TO CATCH POSSIBLE REPEAT INCIDENTS.

column168: ON MARCH, 13 2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 1:25 AM DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN A MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  ON HIS WAY TO HIS LAST DELIVERY OF THE NIGHT AND CARRYING 10,232 GALLONS OF GASOLINE, THE TANKER TRAILER WAS STRUCK BY A THIRD PARTY VEHICLE AT THE LOAD HEADS.  A FIRE BROKE OUT ALMOST IMMEDIATELY.  A WITNESS ON THE SCENE CLAIMS THE THIRD PARTY VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED AND HAD RUN A RED LIGHT WHEN IT STRUCK THE TRAILER AT THE PERPENDICULAR ANGLE.  AFTER THE IMPACT THE DRIVER REGAINED CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE AND SAFETY STOPPED IT APPROXIMATELY 100YDS FROM THE POINT OF IMPACT.  HE EMERGED FROM THE TRACTOR AS FLAMES ENGULFED HIS TRAILER AND THE THIRD PARTY VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER RAN TO A NEARBY CONVENIENCE STORE AND CALLED 911.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FLAMES IN APPROXIMATELY 20 TO 25 MINUTES.  IPT WAS CALLED, POLLUTION CONTROL SERVICE DISPATCHED, AND A FULL CLEAN UP EXECUTED.  THE TANKER WAS PUMPED OFF AND TRACTOR & TRAILER WERE TAKEN TO IMPOUND WHILE POLICE PERFORMED THEIR INVESTIGATION.  THE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN THE FATALITY OF THE THIRD PARTY VEHICLE DRIVER.

ADJACENT TO THE STOP SIGN IS A CURVED RADIUS ALLOWING FOR A RIGHT TURN TO THE SOUTH BOUND ACCESS ROAD TO I-27.  IT WAS IN THIS TURN AREA THAT THE SPEED OF THE TRUCK CAUSED THE LOAD TO SHIFT TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE TURN, CAUSING THE RIGHT SIDE WHEELS TO LEAVE THE ROADWAY.  SCUFFING ON THE ROADWAY AND CURBING CONTAINED ALUMINUM MARKINGS WHERE THE ALUMINUM WHEELS RIMS AND THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER WERE ABRADED BY THE ROAD SURFACE. IT APPEARS THAT THE TRAILER OVERTURNED AS IT CAME OUT OF THE CURVE; FORWARD MOMENTUM WAS ARRESTED BY THE TOP PORTION OF THE TRUCK CAB STRIKING THE GUARD POSTS SUPPORTING THE LEFT SIDE GUARD RAIL.  THE TOP OF THE TRAILER, ON ITS' LEFT SIDE, CAME TO REST AGAINST THE ROADWAY OPENED SEVERAL SMALL HOLES IN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER ALLOWING REGULAR UNLEADED GASOLINE TO LEAK OUT ONTO THE ROAD, THE ROADSIDE WHERE IN THE GUARD RAIL WAS SITUATED AND INTO A CONCRETE FLUME ADJACENT TO I-27 SOUTH BOUND.  THE TANK SIDE WALL WAS HOLED RATHER THAN SPLIT AND RUPTURED; HAD IT BEEN SPLIT OPEN, ALL OF THE PRODUCT WOULD HAVE BEEN RELEASED AT ONCE.  AS IT WAS, THE LEAKAGE WAS SUSTAINED OVER A PERIOD OF SEVERAL HOURS.  WITNESSES CALLED 911 AND RESPONSE WAS VIRTUALLY IMMEDIATE.  CITY WORK CREWS WERE NEARBY AND WERE CALLED IN TO PLACE A DAM IN THE DRAINAGE FLUME TO PREVENT THE FLOW OF GASOLINE FROM ENTERING A NEARBY CREEK BED.  FIRE DEPARTMENT CREWS ATTEMPTED TO PLUG THE TRAILER HOLES THAT THEY COULD REACH AND WERE SOMEWHAT SUCCESSFUL.  WITH SEVERAL FIRE TRUCKS AND CREWS ON SITE, AND A FOAM TRUCK ON SITE, A LOCAL TERMINAL WAS CALLED IN TO ATTEMPT TO DRAFT PRODUCT OUT OF THE OVERTURNED TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 900 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED IN THIS ATTEMPT.  AS THE REQUEST THE FIRE CHIEF, A VACUUM TRUCK, OPERATED BY PATE TRUCKING OF LEVELLAND, WAS CALLED IN AND POSITIONED TO DRAFT GASOLINE AND WATER CONTAINED BEHIND THE DAM IN THE DRAINAGE FLUME. BOLER EQUIPMENT CO, OUR HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONDER, WAS CALLED IN AND WAS ON THE SCENE, WHEN WE ARRIVED FROM SAN ANGELO AT 12:25 PM.  THEY AND THE LUBBOCK FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE INSTRUMENTAL IN PREVENTING THE FURTHER ESCAPE OF GASOLINE INTO THE SURROUNDING AREA.  UPON ARRIVING ON SCENE, WE FOUND A DISCUSSION UNDERWAY AS TO SAFEST WAY TO UPRIGHT THE TRUCK AND TRAILER.  WE REQUESTED THAT BEFORE AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO UPRIGHT THE TRAILER, THAT THE TRAILER BELLY LINES ARE REMOVED AND THE BELLY FLANGES AND VALVES BE REMOVED IN ORDER TO REMOVE THE PRODUCT REMAINING ON BOARD.  WHEN THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED, FOAM WAS SPRAYED OVER THE AREA AND A TANKER UNIT WAS BACKED IN AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS DRAFTED OUT OF THE FOUR COMPARTMENTS; AN ADDITIONAL 500 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED FOR A TOTAL OF 1400 GALLONS. DURING UNLOADING AT ALLEGHENY WAREHOUSE, THE PITTSBURGH LOCAL DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD FALLEN OVER AND WAS LEAKING THROUGH ITS BUNG.  SOME OF THE LIQUID HAD LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND UNDER THE TRAILER WHERE IT HAD BEEN PARKED.  ALSO, THAT DRUM AND TWO OTHERS WERE BULGING AT THEIR MIDDLES.  SEVERAL OF THE DRUMS HAVE RESIDUE ON THEIR HEADS AND APPEAR TO HAVE BEEN VENTING.  AFTER DISCUSSION BETWEEN THE DRIVER, THE CONSIGNEE AND HAZMAT IT WAS LEARNED THAT THE BUNGS ARE LEFT LOOSE BY THE SHIPPER DELIBERATELY IN ORDER TO RELIEVE PRESSURE BUILD UP WITHIN THE DRUMS.  THE CONSIGNEE AGREED THAT WE SHOULD OVERPACK ANY BULGING DRUMS, LEAVING THE LIDS OFF.  THE DRIVER, ASSISTED BY AN ALLEGHENY EMPLOYEE, OVERPACKED THREE DRUMS.  ONE DRUM THAT HAD ACTUALLY LEAKED WAS PLACED INTO A PLASTIC OVERPACK.  TWO OTHERS THAT WERE BULGING BUT NOT LEAKING WERE PUT INTO 85 GALLON STEEL OVERPACKS.  THE DRIVER USED SPILL PADS AND OIL DRY TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND FROM THE AREA UNDER THE TRAILER.  NONE OF THE LIQUID HAD IMPACTED ANY WATERWAY ACCESS.  ON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY, THEY DETERMINED THAT IT WAS NOT SAFE TO REMOVE THE DRUMS AS ORIGINALLY PLANNED.  THEY ASKED TO PURCHASE THE OVERPACKS FROM US.

AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE, THEY FOUND THICK LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ONE CARTON HAD BEEN FORKED, CAUSING LEAKAGE FROM AT LEAST ONE CAN IN THE CARTON.  THE MATERIAL HAD SPREAD OVER FIVE ADDITIONAL CARTONS AS WELL AS ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ALL SIX CARTONS WERE REFUSED. THE MATERIAL HAD SPREAD AROUND THE TRAILER FLOOR TO SUCH AN EXTENT AS TO PRECLUDE MAKING OTHER DELIVERIES OR PICK UPS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING A CLAY ABSORBENT AND PACKED INTO A DRUM.

A SHIPMENT OF 240 CARTONS ON TWELVE PALLETS ARRIVED ON A SHUTTLE FROM J3. DURING STRIPPING OF THE TRAILER, THE UNLOADER FOUND ONE CARTON LYING ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS ON A SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET, TWO TIERS HIGH, TEN CARTONS ON END PER TIER.  THE DOCK SUPERVISOR STATES THAT THE SHRINK WRAP DID NOT COMPLETELY ENCOMPASS THE TOP TIER OF ONE OF THE PALLETS.  DURING TRANSIT, ONE CARTON FELL TO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND BROKE OPEN, SPILLING ABOUT A POUND OF CONTENTS ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. IN A CONFERENCE CALL BETWEEN HAZMAT, CHEMTREC, THE J1 DOCK SUPERVISOR AND BILL BURKET OF BAYER CORP., MR BURKET ASKED TO HAVE THE DAMAGED CARTON PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD FOR A RETURN AUTHORIZATION.  HE ALSO GAVE INSTRUCTIONS FOR THE CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLAGE.
UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE THREE BAGS WERE DISCOVERED RIPPED.  THE SPILL MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PACKED INTO A BAG.  ALL OF THE FREIGHT WAS ACCEPTED.

column168: A RESIDUE TANK CAR HAD BEEN RETURNED EMPTY FROM OUR CUSTOMER AFTER UNLOADING. AN EMERGENCY WAS DECLARED AND THE EMERGENCY TEAM RESPONDED AND SECURED THE AREA.  A THERMOMETER PLACED IN THE THERMOWELL INDICATED THAT THE CAR WAS AT AMBIENT TEMPERATURE (65 DEGREES F).  AREA MONITORING WAS PERFORMED AND ZERO LEVELS OF ETHYLENE OXIDE WAS DETECTED.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE LOADING RACK AND ZERO EMISSIONS WERE DETECTED FROM THE SAFETY VALVE.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A PRODUCT HEEL AND THE CAR WAS DEPRESSURED TO THE UNIT VENT SYSTEM.  THE CAR WAS STRIPPED OF ETHYLENE OXIDE AND THE SAFETY VALVE WAS REMOVED AND BENCH TESTED BY A RAIL CAR CONTRACT REPAIR COMPANY.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF VALVE ABNORMALITY OR DEFECTS.  EVIDENCE SUGGESTS THAT THE CUSTOMER OVERPRESSURED THE CAR WITH NITROGEN DURING OFF-LOADING.  CUSTOMER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH THEM TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: CONTAINER WAS RECEIVED AT MARINE TERMINAL FROM RAIL TERMINAL ON 3/8/04.  ON 3/15/04 US COAST GUARD DISCOVERED SLOW LEAK DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION. TERMINAL STAFF INITIATED HAZMAT SPILL RESPONSE.  ACTI WAS CALLED TO CLEAN-UP.  ACT 1 WAS CONTRACTED DIRECTLY BY SHIPPER.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1715 HOURS, THE FACILITY EXPERIENCED A SPILL EVENT INVOLVING SULFURIC ACID DURING THE TRANSFER OPERATION FROM A RAILCAR TO A STORAGE VESSEL.  THE ACTUAL RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF A TRANSFER HOSE FAILURE.  EMPLOYEES WORKING IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO THE TRANSFER OPERATION WITNESSED THE RELEASE AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HONEYWELL'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FOR INITIATION OF TRANSFER TERMINATION AND REMEDIAL ACTIONS. OPERATIONS PERSONNEL QUICKLY TERMINATED THE TRANSFER AND RELEASE BY CLOSING THE ISOLATION VALVES AT THE RAILCAR AND PUMPING STATION.  IN ADDITION, HONEYWELL EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE POSITIVE SHUT-OFF VALVE IN THE FACILITY'S SEWER SYSTEM, WHICH DISCHARGES TO LPDES PERMITTED OUTFALL 003. THIS ACTION RE-DIRECTED THE NORMAL OUTFALL 003 FLOW TO THE WASTEWATER TREATMENT FACILITY AND PREVENTED ANY MATERIAL FROM ESCAPING THROUGH AN UNTREATED DIRECT DISCHARGE SYSTEM.  AS A RESULT, NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED BEYOND THE FACILITY AND NO PH DEVIATIONS WERE RECORDED OUTSIDE THE NORMAL PERMITTED RANGE.  THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE SPILL EVENT IS ALMOST ENTIRELY PAVED WITH CONCRETE.  A SMALL SECTION OF SOIL HAVING A LIMESTONE COVERING WAS ALSO AFFECTED.  THE LIMESTONE PROVIDED SOME NEUTRALIZATION OF THE ACID MATERIAL, HOWEVER, ADDITIONAL MEASURES WERE IMPLEMENTED TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL SITE.  RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS FLUSHED THE ENTIRE AREA AFFECTED BY THE SPILL WITH WATER SEVERAL TIMES.  THE COLLECTED WATER WAS THEN ROUTED TO HONEYWELL'S WASTEWATER TREATMENT UNIT FOR FURTHER NEUTRALIZATION AND PROCESSING.  BETWEEN FLUSHES, HONEYWELL TESTED THE PH OF THE EXPOSED SURFACE AREA OF SOIL USING PH PAPER UNTIL APPROXIMATE NEUTRAL PH WAS ACHIEVED.  NOTIFICATION TO THE STATE POLICE EMERGENCY HOT LINE OF THE INCIDENT WAS IMMEDIATELY PROVIDED AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HOURS, WHICH WAS FOLLOWED BY A NOTIFICATION TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) (REPORT#715665).  THE ESTIMATED ON-SITE SPILL QUANTITY OF 2,550 LBS IS BASED UPON INVENTORY MASS BALANCING.  BASED ON OUR ASSESSMENT, THE RELEASE OF SULFURIC ACID DID NOT ESCAPE BEYOND THE SITE OF THE FACILITY AND COULD NOT REASONABLY BE EXPECTED TO HAVE ESCAPED BEYOND THE SITE OF THE FACILITY. NEVERTHELESS, OUT OF AN ABUNDANCE OF CAUTION AND AS A MATTER OF POLICY, HONEYWELL IMMEDIATELY MADE A VERBAL NOTIFICATION TO THE STATE POLICE ON THIS MATTER.  HOWEVER, WE DO NOT BELIEVE THE SPILL EVENT MET ANY OF THE NOTIFICATION CRITERIA PROVIDED IN LAC 33:10111.B.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE FREE PRODUCT ON HIS PANTS.  HE CHANGED HIS CLOTHING AND REPORTED NO HEALTH EFFECTS.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED, AFFECTING THE TRAILER, THE DOCK, AND THE ASPHALT YARD, WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED WITH AMPHOMAG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENTS, AMPHOMAG, RAGS, A WHISKBROOM AND DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED CARTON, AND LEAKING JUG WERE PLACED INTO ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND TWO, FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS.  ALL THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE THREE AFFECTED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LYING ON IT'S SIDE NEAR THE HALF-WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING DRUM AND IT WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column42: HYDROBROMIC ACID, WITH MORE THAN 49 PERCENT HYDROBROMIC ACID
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE MOVING FREIGHT ON THE DOCK, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TOP OF ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM.  APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A UNDETERMINED PACKAGING FAILURE; THE BUNG OR SEAL WAS POSSIBLY FAULTY, ALLOWING THE FREE PRODUCT TO SEEP OUT ONTO THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG.  THE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO ONE THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DRM AND THE USED AMPHOMAG WERE PLACED INTO ONE NINETY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FIRST-QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE ONE JUG WAS DAMAGED AND THAT THE REMAINING THREE WERE UNAFFECTED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE JUG WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING, CAUSING THE CARTON TO FALL TO THE TRAILER FLOOR DURING TRANSIT. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENTS, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED BOTTLE WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE THREE UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE CLEANED, RECOUPED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE MARKHAM, IL FACILITY ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. UPON INITIAL DISCOVERY TWO PEOPLE WERE EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT VIA INHALATION.  THE TWO EMPLOYEES WERE TREATED WITH FIRST AID, SENT TO THE HOSPITAL, TREATED AGAIN THEN RELEASED.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING AMMONIA AND CLAY ABSORBENT.  THE MATERIAL WAS PACKED INTO A DRUM. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PACKED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WILL BE RETURNED TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER.  THE SPILL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WILL BE PLACED IN THE HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE AREA TO BE DISPOSED OF BY AN OUTSIDE VENDOR.

ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL REMOVED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: 55 GALLON (11) DRUMS WERE LOADED ON PLT WITH NO CARDBOARD IN BETWEEN DRUMS AND PLT.  NAILS FROM PLT DUG INTO DRUMS DURING TRANSIT.  AS DRUMS WERE BEING UNLOADED, A DRUM WAS PUSHED BY THE WALL OF TRAILER AND SLID ACROSS THE NAILS CAUSING A SLICE IN PLASTIC DRUM.  WE IMMEDIATELY APPLIED SODA ASH, THEN DRY SWEEP TO CONTROL LEAK.  PUT EVERYTHING IN PLASTIC BAGS TO BE PICKED BY HAZ WASTE TEAM.  INFORMED SHIPPER THAT CARDBOARD NEED TO BE BETWEEN PLT AND DRUMS.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE JUG WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING THREE JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE CARTON WAS DUE TO THE CARTON WAS DUE TO THE CARTON BEING CRUSHED IN HANDLING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED JUG WAS PLACED IN A FIVE GALLON OVERPACK CONTAINER AND WILL BE HELD WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED BOTTLE WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, A LONG PIECE OF FREIGHT, WITH ONE, THREE HUNDRED CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING ONE USED ENGINE STACKED ON TOP OF IT, WAS PULLED OUT OF THE TRAILER.  THE CARTON TIPPED OVER ONTO THE DOCK.  APPROXIMATELY THREE-QUARTERS OF A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED, AFFECTED SOME PLASTIC WRAP, AND WERE CONTAINED TO THE DOCK.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING A TYVEK SUIT, GOGGLES, GLOVES, BOOTIES, PARTICULATE ABSORBENTS, AND ABSORBENT TOWELS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE CARTON, THE USED ENGINE, AND THE PLASTIC WRAP WERE DECONTAMINATED, RECOUPED, AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE; THE DRUM WAS DENTED ON ONE RIB ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM, TOWARDS THE TOP. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TWENTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO ONE, SIXTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING, ONE, THREE-HUNDRED GALLON PLASTIC TOTE WAS PUNCTURED DURING LOADING.  APPROXIMATELY THIRTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED SOME ASPHALT.  THE FUNKSTOWN FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WASHINGTON COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  THE FUNKSTOWN FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED DOWN ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE. H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENTS AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO FOUR, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS, FOUR, FIFTY GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS AND SIX, THIRTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS.  ALL THREE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING TOTE AND A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY DRUM CONTAINING SOME OF THE REMAINING MATERIAL FROM THE TOTE WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THIS IS THE ONLY FREIGHT IN THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY POUND PLASTIC BAG WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION A BROOM AND A DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND LEAKING BAG WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

UPON UNLOADING AT TERMINAL DRUM WAS FOUND WITH DENT AND CREASE IN THE CENTER OF DRUM.  SHIPMENT WAS DENTED AT SOME POINT EITHER AT LOADING OR UNLOADING.  WHICH CAUSED THE DRUM TO LEAK A SMALL AMOUNT. BELIEVE THE FLEX OF THE DRUM CAUSED THE DENT TO WEAKEN AND LEAK.
DSR ESTERLINE WAS LOADING AND UNLOADING AND UNLOADING SAID FREIGHT WHEN IT SUSTAINED FORKLIFT DAMAGE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE INTERSECTION OF MCLESTER STREET AND TRIPOLI STREET IN ELIZABETH, NEW JERSEY, THE BRIDGE TERMINAL TRANSPORT, INC. DISCOVERED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED.  H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. OF ELIZABETH, NEW JERSEY RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE INVESTIGATION AND CLEANUP. H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL BELOW THE TRAILER AS A PRECAUTION, THEN OFFLOADED THE FREIGHT.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE DAMAGED SIX GALLON STEEL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO ASPHALT.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO DAMAGE TO THE PAIL BY AN UNKNOWN OBJECT.  H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE FREE PRODUCT INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ON THE AREA OF AFFECTED ASPHALT.  H.M.H.T.T.C., INC.  GENERATED TWO, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF WASTE FOR DISPOSAL.  H.M.H.T.T.C., INC. COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE TWO DRUMS AT THE CYCLECHEM INCINERATION FACILITY IN ELIZABETH, NEW JERSEY.  THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND RETURNED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: 3/10/04 18:30 - A CALLER REPORTED THAT A JEVIC TRUCK HAD OVERTURNED ON THE RAMP AT THE I-60 & I-80 INTERCHANGE NEAR SHENAGO TWP., PA.  JEVIC HAZMAT (JHM) WAS NOTIFIED BY THE PA. STATE POLICE.  JHM CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND WAS PLACED INTO CONFERENCE CALL WITH JOHN NICKLIN, DIRECTOR OF MERCER COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, AND BOB CARTER OF MCCUTCHEON ENTERPRISES (MCE), THE CONTACTED SPILL RESPONSE COMPANY.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL EIGHT TOTES HAD BEEN EJECTED FROM THE TRAILER FROM THE ROOF ONCE THE TRAILER OVERTURNED.  THERE WAS AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF LIQUID THAT HAD LEAKED FROM THE CONTAINERS, SOME OF WHICH HAD ENTERED A LOCAL STREAM.  THE SPILL CLEAN UP PLAN WILL CALL FOR: MCE TO SEND A TANKER TRUCK TO THE SPILL CLEAN UP SITE AND TRANSFER THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE NALCON D3T-A INTO THE TANKER.  AT DAYLIGHT IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE NALCON D3T-A HAD ENTERED THE LOCAL STREAM.  DEAD FISH AND FROGS WERE FOUND UP TO TWO MILES AWAY. 1356 GALLONS OF NALCON D3T-A WAS PUMPED INTO A TANKER.  THE TANKER LEFT SITE ON 3/11/04 AND WILL BE SENT TO W.T.I. IN EAST LIVERPOOL, OH FOR DISPOSAL (INCINERATION).  GARY WASINAK OF THE PA DEP WAS ON SITE DIRECTING THE SOIL REMOVAL PROCESS.  THE SOIL IN THE IMMEDIATE SPILL AREA WAS SOAKED AND HAD A PH OF 14.  THE SOIL WAS CAUSTIC IN NATURE.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 25 TONS OF SOIL WAS REMOVED.  THE SOIL WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY MCCUTCHEON ENTERPRISES.  OFFICER JOE MORRIS OF THE PA FISH & GAME COMMISSION IS ON SITE TO SUPERVISE THE STREAM CLEAN UP.  MR. NICKLEN STATED THAT THE F & G COMMISSION HAS FOUND LIVE FISH A MILE UP STREAM FROM WHERE THE LAST DEAD FISH WAS FOUND.  MR NICKLEN ALSO STATED THAT THE COMMISSION HAS TAKEN WATER SAMPLES NEAR THE SPILL SITE TO DETERMINE CONTAMINATION. WILLIE WASHINGTON OF NALCO WAS CALLED BY JEVIC HAZMAT TO BE INFORMED OF THE DAYS EVENTS.  THE REMEDIATION OF THE SITE WAS COMPLETED ON 3/16/04.  ALL OF THE REMOVED SOIL HAS BEEN REPLACED AND HOG BACK RUN IS RETURNING TO NORMAL.

DRIVER WAS TRAVELING U.S. 60 EAST IN HUNTINGTON, WV.  DRIVER CAME OUT FROM ONE TRAFFIC LIGHT TO ANOTHER WHEN IT TURNED YELLOW.  THE VEHICLES IN FRONT OF HIM STOPPED AND HE HIT HIS BRAKES IN AN EMERGENCY STOP.  THE MATERIAL CAME ALL THE WAY FORWARD TO THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND OUT OF THE TOP BETWEEN THE TARP AND THE TRAILER BODY ITSELF.  THE TRAILER WAS COMPLETELY SECURE WITH THE TIEDOWNS IN PLACE WHEN THE MATERIAL CAME OUT.  THE 2,360 LBS WEIGHT DISCREPANCY ALSO INCLUDES ANY LOSS IN WEIGHT FROM SPENT FUEL FOR THE TRIP FROM HUNTINGTON, WV TO PALMERTON, PA.  THE MATERIAL AND THE AREA WERE CLEANED UP BY THE WEST VIRGINIA DEPT. OF HIGHWAYS AND ECOFIRST OF WEST VIRGINIA AND THE WV EPA AND USA EPA INVOLVED.  DRIVERS WERE WARNED TO LEAVE A SAFE STOPPING DISTANCE TO PREVENT OCCURRENCES LIKE THIS IN THE FUTURE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING IN CHATTANOOGA, TENNESSEE AT THE OX HIGHWAY AND EVERETT INTERSECTION THE VEHICLE'S BRAKES WENT OUT RESULTING IN A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  WILSON TRUCKING CORPORATION CONTRACTED FERGUSON-HARBOUR, INC. OF CHATTANOOGA, TENNESSEE TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  UPON INVESTIGATION, FERGUSON-HARBOUR, INC. DISCOVERED A CARTON CONTAINING ONE DAMAGED 2.6 GALLON CONTAINER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. ALSO RELEASED FROM THE VEHICLE'S SADDLE TANK WAS TEN GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.  FERGUSON-HARBOUR, INC. APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN AND REMOVE THE DIESEL FUEL AND FREE PRODUCT FROM THE AFFECTED ASPHALT SURFACE. THE WRECKER SERVICE THAT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT, MOSTELLAR'S, WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE IMPACTED ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS SENT BACK TO THE WILSON TRUCKING FACILITY IN CHATTANOOGA, TENNESSEE PENDING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.  THERE IS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 136 AT THE 136 CONNECTOR, APPROXIMATELY 6 MILES NORTHWEST OF CALHOUN, GEORGIA, THE EAGLE SYSTEMS, INC. TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT OVER-TURNED.   APPROXIMATELY 5,400 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED, AFFECTING SOIL AND THE SNAKE CREEK.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO DAMAGE TO THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER.  THE GEORGIA STATE POLICE, THE GEORGIA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, THE GEORGIA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES, THE GORDON COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY, THE GORDON COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE GORDON COUNTY POLICE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT SITE.  THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED.  MARION ENVIRONMENTAL INC. OF CHATTANOOGA, TENNESSEE RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  ALL WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE AQUA TREAT WASTE-WATER TREATMENT PLANT IN CHATTANOOGA, TENNESSEE.  NO SPILL-RELATED INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 61 IN HANNIBAL, MISSOURI, THE SCHIBER TRUCK COMPANY, INC. DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASING FROM THE CARGO TANK.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED SOIL.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE DOME LID AT THE TOP FRONT OF THE CARGO TANK.  THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES, THE HANNIBAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE HANNIBAL POLICE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. PERSONNEL FROM BOTH ENDURO INDUSTRIES AND SCHIBER TRUCK COMPANY, INC. RESPONDED TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP.  VACUUM TRUCKS AND A BACK-HOE WERE USED TO REMOVE THE FREE PRODUCT AND THE AFFECTED SOIL FROM THE SITE. SCHIBER TRUCK COMPANY, INC. TRANSPORTED THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP TO THEIR FACILITY IN HARTFORD, ILLINOIS FOR ANALYTICAL TESTING AND DISPOSAL COORDINATION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

FIVE GONDOLA CARS IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TRAIN Q35104 WERE SET OUT ON A SIDING AT FOSTORIA, OH BECAUSE THE TARPS COVERING THE MATERIAL HAD COME LOOSE.  CSXT485907, CSXT485570, CSXT709018, CSXT 486209, AND CSXT486922 ALL CONTAINED HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, NOS (CONTAINS LEAD, CHROME, TOLUENE). CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, BASF CORP. AND ADVISED THEM THAT THE TARPS ON 2 OF THE CARS, CSXT786209 AND CSXT485570, HAD BEEN BLOWN AWAY AND THE TARPS ON THE REST OF THE CARS HAD COME LOOSE AND WERE NOT PROPERLY SECURED.  IN ADDITION, ALL THE CARS WERE DRIPPING WATER FROM SEVERAL DRAINS HOLES IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CARS.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CARS AND LIQUID LEAKAGE.  THE WASTE PROFILE PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER SHOWED THE MATERIAL CONTAINED VERY LOW CONCENTRATIONS OF HEAVY METALS INCLUDING LEAD, CHROMIUM AND ARSENIC.  THE CONTRACTOR TOOK SAMPLES OF THE LIQUID FOR ANALYSIS.  THE CONTRACTOR HAD TO ORDER NEW TARPS AND COMPLETED INSTALLING NEW TARPS, AND SECURING THE LOOSE TARPS ON 03-08.  ALL THE DRAIN HOLES IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CARS WERE PLUGGED USING BOTH WOODEN AND RUBBER PLUGS.  THE CONTRACTOR ESTIMATED APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF WATER LEAKED FROM EACH OF THE 5 CARS BEFORE ALL THE DRAIN HOLES WERE PLUGGED.

THE CONTRACTOR TOOK SAMPLES OF THE LIQUID FOR ANALYSIS.  THE CONTRACTOR HAD TO ORDER NEW TARPS AND COMPLETED INSTALLING NEW TARPS, AND SECURING THE LOOSE TARPS ON 03-08.  ALL THE DRAIN HOLES IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CARS WERE PLUGGED USING BOTH WOODEN AND RUBBER PLUGS.  THE CONTRACTOR ESTIMATED APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF WATER LEAKED FROM EACH OF THE 5 CARS BEFORE ALL THE DRAIN HOLES WERE PLUGGED.

column168: LTCX 1807, LOAD ARGON, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S ROSE LAKE YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS, IL.  THE MECHANICAL FOREMAN REPORTED THE CAR WAS LEAKING LIQUID PRODUCT FROM INSIDE THE VALVE CABINET ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  PRAXAIR, INC WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND THEY RESPONDED A TECHNICIAN TO THE YARD TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE TECHNICIAN FOUND THE PACKING NUT ON THE LIQUID VALVE WAS LOOSE AND THE LIQUID VALVE HAD VIBRATED OPEN SLIGHTLY.  THE CAP ON THE LIQUID LINE WAS ALSO LOOSE.  HE CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT.  HE REMOVED THE LIQUID LINE CAP, INSPECTED THE TEFLON GASKET, AND INSTALLED THE CAP WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A DAMAGED DRUM WHILE ON THE DOCK AT THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. FACILITY.  APPARENTLY, ONE (1) 110-POUND FIBER DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  APPROXIMATELY .5 OUNCE OF THE POWDER-LIKE SUBSTANCE WAS RELEASED ONTO THE DOCK.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PPE.  THE PRODUCT WAS SWEPT, AND THE AFFECTED AREA WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER.  CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE (1) 5-GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM, ALONG WITH THE PPE.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS MENDED, AND OVERPACKED INTO ONE (1) 55-GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: ON 3/4/04 A PKG WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION THAT WAS WET, AND WAS TURNING HANDS WHITE WHEN TOUCHED.  THIS PKG WAS ONE THAT WAS DAMAGED BY THE LEAKING HAZ PKG. (UNKNOWN AT THE TIME), SEVERAL OTHERS WERE BROUGHT TO ME THAT WERE ALSO WET.  APPROX TIME WAS 845 TO 900 AM.  APPROXIMATELY 1145, RECEIVED A CALL FROM JAMES MITCHELL ADVISING HE HAD JUST RECEIVED A PKG THAT WAS DAMAGED AND LEAKING HYDROGEN PEROXIDE 35%. I ASKED IF PKG WAS MARKED AS SUCH, AND WAS ADVISE THE PKG HAD NO MARKINGS OF ANY KIND TO WARN OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, APPROX 1215 I CALL HAZ HOTLINE TO ADVISE.  WE CONTACTED THE DRIVER WHO HAD DELVD PKG TO ADVISE.  HE AND PASSENGER COMPLAINED OF BURNING EYES & BREATHING PROBLEMS.  WE SENT TO DOCTOR FOR EXAMINATION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS, 3-20-04, JEFF FUENNING, TRANSPORTATION SUPERVISOR, APRIA HEALTHCARE, TUSCON, AZ. WHILE CONDUCTING A WALK AROUND SAFETY INSPECTION BEFORE LEAVING THE BRANCH FOUND THAT SUBJECT(S) UNKNOWN HAD SLIGHTLY OPENED A FILL ON A FILL LINE FROM THEIR 6000 GAL STAND TANK OVER THE WEEKEND RESULTING IN 100" (APPROX. 2320 GALLONS) OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (LOX) TO DRAIN OUT ONTO THE CONCRETE CATCH PAD.  ENTRY WAS MADE TO THE ENCLOSURE AND THE VALVE WAS TURNED OFF.  THE TUCSON POLICE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED (REPORT #0403200507).  THE AREA WAS SECURED WHEN THE RESIDUAL EVAPORATED.  THERE WAS NO COLLATERAL DAMAGE AND NO INJURIES. THE STAND TANK IS LOCATED IN A SECURED AREA AND THERE WAS NO SIGNS OF ENTRY.  ENTRY WAS APPARENTLY MADE BY CLIMBING THE FENCE.  FUENNING STATES THAT WHILE CLOSING THE BRANCH ON FRIDAY, MARCH 19TH 2003, HE HAD PERSONALLY INSPECTED THE STAND TANK.  HE STATES THAT THERE WAS NO FOG OR ANY INDICATION THERE WAS ANY LEAK.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, OR ANY COLLATERAL DAMAGE RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0735AM I RECEIVED A CALL AT HOME FROM DAN CARPENTER WHO WAS THE PHARMACIST ON DUTY.  HE HAD JUST BEEN CONTACTED BY WEST HARTFORD FIRE CHIEF JOHN OATES, CONCERNING AN ACCIDENT THAT INVOLVED ONE OF OUR DELIVERY VEHICLES.  THE VEHICLE IN QUESTION HAD FLIPPED SEVERAL TIMES AND THE CONTENTS HAD BEEN EXPELLED.  SOME OF THE AMMO CANS HAD OPENED AND THERE WERE PIGS ON THE GROUND.  ACCORDING TO CT DEP, ONE OF THE PIGS WAS OPEN AND SOME MATERIAL HAD LEAKED OUT.  AT THIS POINT I CONTACTED CHIEF OATES AND GOT HIS REPORT THEN I IMMEDIATELY WENT TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  WHEN I ARRIVED, CT DEP, CT STATE POLICE, AND THE WEST HARDFORD FIRE DEPT WERE ON THE SCENE.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON INTERSTATE 84 HEADING EASTBOUND IN THE VICINITY OF EXIT 43. ( WEST HARTFORD)   THE TRUCK HAD ALREADY BEEN PLACED ON THE BACK OF A FLATBED TOW TRUCK.  THERE WERE DELIVERY CANS DISPERSED ON THE GROUND, SOME OF WHICH WERE INTACT AND SOME THAT WERE NOT INTACT.  THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY 25-30 PIGS ON THE GROUND THAT HAD COME OUT OF DELIVERY CANS.  THEY ALL SEEMED TO BE INTACT.  THE CT DEP REPRESENTATIVE IN CHARGE WAS SURVEYING AN AREA OF THE ROADWAY THAT HAD ONE OPEN PIG THAT WAS LEAKING MATERIAL.  MICHAEL FIRSICK (CT DEP) ASKED ME SOME CURSORY QUESTIONS AS TO THE CONTENTS OF THE VEHICLE AND THEN CONTINUED TO SURVEY THE AREA.  THE OTHER DEP REPRESENTATIVE WAS SURVEYING THE AREA  WHERE THE DELIVERY CANS AND PIGS WERE ON THE GROUND.  ONCE HE HAD CLEARED THE AREA, I WAS INSTRUCTED TO BEGIN CLEANING UP THE CANS/PIGS.  DICK IDENT, CSA SUPERVISOR, HAD ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT THIS POINT WITH A METER, GLOVES AND EMPTY DELIVERY CANS.  SINCE SEVERAL OF THE CANS THAT WERE IN THE ACCIDENT WERE DAMAGED, WE NEEDED TO USE THE NEW DELIVERY CANS THAT HE BROUGHT.  ALL THE CANS/PIGS WERE COLLECTED AND SECURED IN THE BACK OF DICK'S DELIVERY TRUCK. BY THIS TIME THE DEP HAD DECONTAMINATED THE ROADWAY AND DEEMED THE AREA ACCEPTABLE FOR RELEASE.  AT THAT POINT I RETURNED TO THE PHARMACY AND NOTIFIED WILLIE REGITS AT Q & R. ( 1100AMEST)     NOTE: THE VEHICLE ONLY CONTAINED LIMITED QUANTITY RETURN CANS.  ALL OTHER CANS HAD ALREADY BEEN DELIVERED.  NOTE: THE DRIVER OF OUR TRUCK (LYNNWOOD) WAS INJURED IN THE ACCIDENT.  HE HAD ALREADY BEEN TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL BY THE TIME I ARRIVED AT THE SCENE.  THE EXTENT OF HIS INJURIES ARE NOT KNOWN AT THIS TIME OTHER THAN THEY WERE NOT LIFE-THREATENING.  NOTE:  THERE WAS ANOTHER VEHICLE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT.  THE CONDITION OF THE DRIVER IS NOT KNOWN AT THIS TIME.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE AND ODOR LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY WAS NOTICED. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL TWO METAL CANS AT APPROXIMATELY ONE LITER CAPACITY EACH.  THE LID SEAL ON BOTH CANS APPARENTLY FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SUBSTANCE IDENTIFIED AS A UV SEALER AND TOPCOAT CLEARLY MET THE DEFINITION OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THE TWO CANS EXHIBITED FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABELS AS WELL. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FFA FOR INVESTIGATION.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT WENDY DENT - HENRY/FAA/ATL AT 14:39(CST) ON 03/16/2004.

column168: FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION (FRA) INSPECTOR, ROBERT MCNAMARA, REPORTED TO CHEMTREC THAT WHILE HE WAS CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN WEST SPRINGFIELD, MA, HE DETECTED A PRODUCT ODOR ON THE TOP OF GATX 94664, LOAD BUTYL ACRYLATES.  HE OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING TO INSPECT THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE AND THE VAPOR LINE AND REPORTED HE COULD HEAR A SOUND LIKE LIQUID BUBBLING OR BOILING INSIDE THE TANK CAR.  CHEMTREC CONFERENCED MR MCNAMARA IN WITH CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REPRESENTATIVE.  MR. MCNAMARA INDICATED THERE WAS NO SIGN OF A LIQUID PRODUCT RELEASE AND THE TOP OF THE CAR WAS NOT WARM OR HOT TO THE TOUCH.  THERE WAS A CONCERN THAT THE PRODUCT MIGHT BE POLYMERIZING INSIDE THE TANK.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO ISOLATE IT AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  CHEMTREC CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, ATOFINA, AND CSXT'S LOCAL TRAINMASTER CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, SOLUTIA, AND REQUESTED THEIR ASSISTANCE.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR.  THE CONTRACTOR CHECKED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND FOUND IT TO BE ABOUT 3 PSIG.  THEY OPENED THE MANWAY TO CHECK THE LIQUID PRODUCT AND FOUND ABOUT 13 INCHES OF OUTAGE WITH NO EVIDENCE OF ANY CHEMICAL REACTION.  THEY REMOVED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE TO INSPECT THE SEAT AND FOUND VALVE THREADS COVERED IN TEFLON TAPE AND TEFLON "DOPE" WHICH MAY HAD IMPEDED THE PROPER SEATING OF THE VALVE.  THE EXCESS TEFLON WAS CLEANED FROM THE VALVE AND THE VALVE INSTALLED ON THE CAR.  BOTH THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE WERE KEPT INFORMED OF THE SITUATION AND THEY WERE ADVISED TO HAVE A VACUUM VALVE INSPECTED WHEN THE RESIDUE CAR RETURNED TO ORIGIN.  THEY WAS NO SIGN OF ANY LIQUID OR VAPOR PRODUCT RELEASE AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR ROBERT MCNAMARA FOUND HOKX 112309 TO HAVE RESIDUE OF PRODUCT ON TOP & SIDE OF TANK CAR FROM ACTIVATED PRD-VALVE WHILE IN TRANSPORTATION.  INSPECTOR MCNAMARA INSPECTED PRD-VALVE AT WEST SPRINGFIELD YARD AND FOUND VALVE TO BE SEATED.  NO PRODUCT LEAKING AT THAT TIME.  CAR WAS FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE FOR OUTAGE MEASUREMENT, AND THAT MEASUREMENT TO BE REPORTED TO CSXT AND FRA INSPECTOR MCNAMARA.

column168: DRUM ARRIVED LEAKING IN THE TRAILER.  THE CAP ON THE SHIPMENT HAD FAILED. WE CALLED ONDEO NALCO AND THEY TOLD US THAT THEY HAD A RECALL ON ALL THE CAPS DUE TO MANUFACTURE DEFECTIVENESS.  THE SHIPMENT HAD TIPPED OVER IN TRANSIT, BUT DUE TO A FAULTY CAP THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT.

UPON ARRIVAL AT NATIONAL PRODUCTS, OUR DRIVER WAS MET BY RECEIVER SUPERVISOR AND UNLOADER.  DRIVER PRODUCED DELIVERY LADING AND CERT OF ANALYSIS.  HE WAS DIRECTED TO A CONTAIN AREA THAT HAD 6 POLY TANKS AND DIRECTED TO HOOK UP TO THE UNLOADING PIPE.  AFTER HOOKUP, DRIVER HAD TO FIND UNLOADER AND RETURN WITH HIM TO DELIVERY AREA.  ONCE THERE, DRIVER TENDERED ALL COPIES OF PAPERWORK WITH WERE THEN SIGNED BY UNLOADER, JEFFERY BRADFORD.  THE PAPERWORK CORRECTLY IDENTIFIED THE CHEMICAL BEING DELIVERED AS "RQ, HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION, 8, UN 1791, PG III".  MR. BRADFORD SIGNED THE LADING AND THE PRE DELIVERY WAIVER ON THE CARTAGE TICKET STATING THAT WE WERE CONNECTED TO THE PROPER UNLOADING CONNECTION.  DRIVER GAVE SIGNED COPIES TO BRADFORD AND BRADFORD TOLD HIM HE COULD BEGIN UNLOADING DRIVER BEGAN UNLOADING AND BRADFORD RETURNED TO INSIDE PLANT.  APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES INTO UNLOADING PROCESS, DRIVER OBSERVED A VAPOR CLOUD EMITTING FROM THE TOP OF TANKS.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ACTIVATED EMERGENCY SHUT DOWN SYSTEM ON CARGO TANK, STOPPING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  DRIVER WENT TO PLANT ENTRANCE TO ADVISE OF EMERGENCY SITUATION AND WAS MET BY EMPLOYEES EXITING PLANT. DRIVER ADVISED EMPLOYEES TO MOVE TO A PLACE OF SAFETY UPWIND AND AWAY FROM PLANT.  AN EVACUATION OF PLANT CONTINUED.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS FROM LAPORTE COUNTY FIRE AND HAZ-MAT ARRIVED ON SCENE AND TOOK OVER SCENE. ALTOM SAFETY DEPT. NOTIFIED AND I RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  (SEE INCIDENT REPORT ATTACHED).  UPON ARRIVAL, I WAS MET BY ROGER WOLFF OF THE LAPORTE COUNTY HAZ-MAT TEAM.  MR. WOLFF ADVISED THAT 16 WORKERS HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED TO LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT.  I WAS JOINED BY NATIONAL PRODUCTS PLANT MANAGER, RAY ALLEN WHO ADVISED THAT NRC HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY HIM (REPORT #716466 OPERATOR RAWLS).  MR. WOLFF ADVISED THAT THE INJURED WORKERS WERE TREATED FOR RESPIRATORY DISTRESS DUE TO CHLORINE GAS EXPOSURE WHICH RESULTED WHEN THE HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION WAS MISTAKENLY UNLOADED INTO POLY TANKS CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID. THE BALANCE OF INFORMATION I CAN PROVIDE AT THIS TIME IS CONTAINED IN THE ATTACHED INCIDENT REPORT.  AS THIS MATTER HAS EVOLVED IT HAS BECOME APPARENT THAT NATIONAL PRODUCTS IS NOT ACCEPTING RESPONSIBILITY IN THE MATTER, BUT RATHER BLAMING THE CARRIER WHICH IS CONTRARY TO ALL FACTS AND EVIDENCE.  THE MATTER WILL UNDOUBTEDLY BE LITIGATED AT SOME POINT IN THE FUTURE. AFTER REVIEW OF FACTS OF THE INCIDENT, I AM CERTAIN THAT THE DRIVER DID EVERYTHING UNDER DIRECT CONTROL OF NATIONAL PRODUCTS PERSONNEL.

(TIM'S TRLR WAS PRE-LOADED FOR HIM, HE WAS UNAWARE OF LEAKING DRUMS).  CONSIGNEE HANDLES THIS FRT ALL THE TIME AND TOOK CARE OF ALL CLEAN-UP.  PER JOHN WILSON, WITH VENTURE, THIS WAS A VERY MINOR INCIDENT AND THERE WILL BE NO REPERCUSSIONS OR CLAIM TO FOLLOW.  ON HOLLANDS END, WE CONTACTED CHEMTREC (REPORT# 03222004017) AND HAD COMMUNICATION W/CAMERON RICHTER OF ERTS.  LOADING DOCKMAN USED DRUM PICKER AND CLAIMS FRT WAS FINE WHEN LOADED.

ICTF SECURITY REPORTED A HAZMAT RELEASE AT THE ICTF YARD IN LONG BEACH CA . THE RELEASE WAS FROM CONTAINER INBU 492311 AND WAS DRIPPING AT A RATE OF THREE TO FOUR DROPS A MINUTE.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED IN WHITE 452. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND THE LADING TO BE 18 EACH, 275 GALLON TOTES.  THE LEAK WAS AT THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER WITH APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT DRIPPING ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THE TOTES HAD BEEN SECURED WITH TY-GARD, WHICH WAS MOSTLY PULLED AWAY FROM THE SIDEWALLS AND HANGING AT THE REAR OF THE TOTES.  A STEEL 2X6 BEAM WAS NAILED TO THE FLOOR AT THE REAR OF THE TOTES.  WHILE THE SECUREMENT APPEARED TO BE ADEQUATE, THE LOADING PATTERN OF THE TOTES PLACED END TO END LENGTH WAYS,AND THE LACK OF A CENTER VOID FILLER, ALLOWED THE TOTES TO MOVE AROUND DURING TRANSIT.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND CONTAINED.  THE SHIPPER, HERCULES, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE TOTES TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  ONE TOTE AT THE RIGHT FRONT OF THE CONTAINER WAS FOUND LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE, DIRECTLY BEHIND THE BOTTOM DISCHARGE VALVE.  IT APPEARS THE WIRE CAGE PROTECTING THE POLY TOTE WORE THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF THE POLY TOTE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO WEEP.  THE TOTES APPEARED TO SHOW SOME WEAR, AND MAY NOT BE NEW.  THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE LEAKING TOTE INTO 55 GALLON POLY DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  IT WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE HARBOR FOR EXPORT VESSEL LOADING.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: ON 3/11/04, DENNIS M. JOHNSON, MANAGER CTS, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD WAS CONDUCTING INSPECTIONS OF TANKCAR AT THE CAMPO YARD, PHOENIX, AZ AND FOUND RAIL CAR SHPX 205919 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY SECURING NUTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  ONE OF THE SECURING NUTS WAS LOOSE HALF WAY UP THE THREADS.  ALL NUTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED, THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE CAR RELEASE TO TRANSPORTATION.

FRANK LERCH, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS ADVISED BY TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, OF LEAKING TANK CAR ECUX 361055, IN THE SETTEGAST YARD ON TRACK R1, MP381.60 BEAUMONT SUB. ON ARRIVAL AT 5:00 PM, MGR. LERCH REPORTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM A FAILED FLANGE GASKET ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVE.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE DROP EVERY FIVE SECONDS.  MGR. LERCH WAS ABLE TO CONTAIN THE LEAK BY SECURING A BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE.  THE RELEASE WAS ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN ONE GALLON WHICH EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.  AFTER DETERMINING THAT THE CAR COULD NOT BE REPAIRED, THE CAR WAS SPOTTED TO THE CAB TRACK FOR TRANSFER. SHIPPER CONTACT WAS MADE WITH LEE RAY KADERLI, EMERGENCY MANAGER FOR EXXON MOBIL VIA CHEM-TREC. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO TANK CAR ECUX 401067 PM ON 3-19-04.  AT 1030 HRS ON 3-19-04, TRANSFER ACTIVITIES BEGAN AND WERE COMPLETED AT 1845 HRS.  TANK CAR ECUX 361055 COULD NOT BE COMPLETELY OFF LOADED INTO TANK CAR ECUX 401067 DUE TO THE SMALLER CAPACITY.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO LOAD THE REMAINING AMOUNT OF PRODUCT INTO A TANK TRUCK.  AFTER COMPLETION OF THE TRANSFER, CAR ECUX 361055 WAS RELEASE TO BE HOME-SHOPPED FOR NECESSARY REPAIRS.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, NOR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

AT 1515 HRS ON 3-19-04, CTS MANAGER LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY CAR DEPT PERSONNEL ADVISING THAT AN ODOR OF AMMONIA WAS COMING FROM TANK CAR PLMX 2541, LOCATED IN TRACK 406 SETTETAST YARD.  UPON INSPECTION, MGR. LERCH DETECTED PRODUCT VENTING FROM THE SEAL BETWEEN THE MANWAY PRESSURE PLATE AND MANWAY NOZZLE.  WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF CTS REGIONAL MANAGER TIM O'BRIEN, EFFORTS TO TIGHTEN THE MANWAY PRESSURE PLATE BOLTS WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  AT THE REQUEST OF MGR. LERCH, THE RMCC WAS DIRECTED TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC.  AFTER FAILING TO REACH THE SHIPPER VIA CHEM-TREC.  DIRECT CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER; NECHES INDUSTRIAL PARK MANAGER BILL CASTLEMAN AND BUCKEY PARKER OF CONTINENTAL NITROGEN AND RESOURCES.  UPON ADVISING MR. PARKER AND CASTLEMAN THE NATURE OF THE RELEASE, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE RESCAR MOBIL RAIL REPAIR RESPOND AND FACILITATE REPAIRS.  ON ARRIVAL OF RESCAR PERSONNEL, AND WITH THE USE OF A FOUR FOOT TORQUE WRENCH ALL PRESSURE PLATE BOLTS WERE PROPERLY TIGHTENED, WHICH SEALED THE CAR FROM FURTHER RELEASE.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, NOR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

PHIL, CENTRAL CALIFORNIA TRACTION COMPANY, REPORTED RAILCAR ACGX 10099 WAS SEEPING PRODUCT FROM A WELDED SEAM ON THE TOP OF THE RAILCAR.  SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS,  JAMES MILLERS INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND A SMALL LEAK FROM AN UPPER SEAM ON THE RIGHT HAND SIDE OF THE CAR.  PRODUCT EVAPORATED BEFORE IT REACHED THE GROUND.  SAHM MILLERS MADE A TEMPORARY REPAIR TO THE LEAK.  THE TANK CAR WAS FORWARDED TO FINAL DESTINATION FOR OFF LOADING.  ONCE OFF LOADED, IT WAS SCHEDULED TO BE SENT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.  MOVEMENT APPROVAL WAS REQUESTED BY CONSIGNEE.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: AT 1500 HRS ON 3-25-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS ADVISED BY THE RMCC THAT COMPANY EMPLOYEE RONNIE COOK, CONDUCTOR HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO A CHEMICAL FROM TANK CAR GPPX 9493.  INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED THAT MR. COOK WAS SWITCHING CAR WHEN MATERIAL SPLASHED OUT OF THE MANWAY OPENING.  MR. COOK INDICATED THE EXPOSURE WAS LIMITED TO HIS CLOTHES, AND THAT HE WENT HOME TO CHANGE, AND LATER RETURNED WITH NO INJURIES REPORTED.  IMMEDIATE RESPONSE AND INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE RELEASED MATERIAL HAD SPILLED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND HAD DRIED.  INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY OPENING REVEALED THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE A COMPOSITION TYPE MATERIAL.  THE GASKET WAS NOTED TO BE CRACKED, BROKEN AND IN NEED OF REPLACEMENT.  MGR. LERCH REMOVED THE DEFECTIVE GASKET AND REPLACED IT WITH A BUTYL NOZZLE GASKET AND SECURED THE CAR BY TIGHTENING THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  AT 1115 HRS ON 3-26-04, MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, KEITH LONG, SR. PRODUCTION SCHEDULER ADVISING OF THE RELEASE AND EXPOSURE.  MR LONG INDICATED MATERIAL IN THE CAR WAS "TOLL OIL PITCH", AND WAS ONLY REGULATED BECAUSE IT WAS A HEAT-ELEVATED MATERIAL, AND THAT IT WAS NON-HAZARDOUS. AFTER ADVISING MR. LONG OF THE RELEASE, HE INDICATED THAT HE WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH THE APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL TO SEE THAT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT WOULD NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, NOR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT.  ORIGINAL PROTECTING SEALS: MANWAY -- AIM-FPGLSR360733.  APPLIED PROTECTING SEALS:  MANWAY -- UPRR CTS -- 0008656.

column168: KENNETH NELSON, SPECIAL AGENT, REPORTED A THREE CAR DERAILMENT AT MP 699.1, CALEXICO SUBDIVISION, INVOLVING UTLX 37632,  LOADED OF PROPANE.   THE THREE CARS, PART OF TRAIN LKE36 29, DERAILED UPRIGHT WITH NO SPILLS OR LEAKS. SYBIL, CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SVCS WAS NOTIFIED AND REPORT NUMBER 04-1708 RECEIVED.  AMANDA. COUNTY DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. DAVE HUDSON, EL CENTRO FIRE CHIEF, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 07:44 PM, MGR. BAVIER REPORTED THERE WAS A SLIGHT LEAK FROM THE CONNECTION OF THE GAUGING DEVICE VALVE BODY TO THE PIPE NIPPLE.  THE LIQUID PRODUCT ESCAPED AND IMMEDIATELY VAPORIZED.  MR BAVIER TIGHTENED THE GAUGING DEVICE VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  RMCC MADE NECESSARY FEDERAL AND STATE AGENCIES.

column168: AT 0835HRS ON 3-30-04, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC, AND ADVISED THAT KEVIN HARRIS, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR NATX 20102 WAS LEAKING AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN THE STRANG YARD, BOWL TRACK #2.  MR. HARRIS STATED A SWITCHMAN DISCOVERED THE RELEASE WHEN EXPOSED TO THE VAPORS.  FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  RMCC MADE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC. AT 9:16 AM, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY ADVISED HE HAD SPOKE TO THE SWITCHMAN WHO REPORTED THAT HE HAD NO DIRECT CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT.  HE STATED THAT HE HAD MINIMAL EXPOSURE TO THE PRODUCT VAPORS AND HAD REPORTED A SLIGHT IRRITATION TO HIS FACE AND EYES.  AFTER RINSING HIS EYES, AND WASHING HIS FACE, HE RESUMED WORK WITH NO FURTHER COMPLAINTS.  MR LERCH DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR IN THE AREA AROUND THE SUMP AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON PER MINUTE.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO SHELL FAILURE, AND COULD NOT BE STOPPED.  IT WAS CONTAINED WITH A CONTAINMENT POOL AND NEUTRALIZING MATERIAL.  RMCC MADE NECESSARY STATE NOTIFICATIONS.  AT 10:01 AM, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED THE SHIPPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO GATX 1933.  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED BY THE SHIPPER FOR TRANSFER OF PRODUCT, CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION.  MANAGER LERCH REPORTED TRANSFER EFFORTS BEGAN AT 01:40 PM AND WERE COMPLETED AT 08:00 PM.  CLEAN-UP OF THE SITE WAS COMPLETED AT 09:30 PM.  THE CONTENTS FROM LEAKING TANKCAR NATX 20102 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANKCAR GATX 1933 UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF MILLENNIUM CHEMICAL PERSONNEL.  AT 09:30 PM ON 3-31-04, MR. LERCH REPORTED THAT GARNER PERSONNEL HAD RETURNED TO THE SITE TO RESUME REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES, AND CLEARED THE AREA AT 11:30 AM.  TANKCAR NATX 20102 WAS TAGGED LEAKING TANK, DO NOT LOAD AND BAD ORDERED FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION. LOADED TANKCAR GATX 1933 WAS BILLED, AND RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, NOR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

DAVID JARREAU, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR DOWX 3302, LOCATED IN THE LIVONIA YARD ON TRACK 306, WAS POSSIBLY VENTING PRODUCT. HOWEVER, THERE WAS NO VISIBLE LEAKAGE NOR VAPOR CLOUD NOR AUDIBLE INDICATION OF LEAKAGE.  THE REPORT WAS BASED ON AN OCCASIONAL PETROLEUM-LIKE ODOR DETECTED NEAR THE TANKCAR.  MR. JARREAU, REPORTED THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS AND HULCHER SERVICES PERSONNEL HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND BOTH RESPONDED. TROOPER LEE LEWIS, LOUISIANA STATE PLACE, AND HULCHER SERVICES WERE ON SCENE COMPLETING SECUREMENT OF THE TANKCAR.  AT 08:40 AM, MANAGER ROBINSON ARRIVED ON SCENE AND CONTACTED MR. KEITH LE BLANC OF HULCHER SERVICES AND TROOPER LEE LEWIS OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE.  LEBLANC AND LEWIS REPORTED THE O RINGS WERE DEFECTIVE AND HAD BEEN SUCCESSFULLY REPLACED.,  THE LEAK WAS SECURED AND THE TANKCAR RETURNED TO SERVICE.

THE PAIL WAS DROPPED DURING HANDLING CAUSING LEAKAGE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED.  UNDAMAGED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

ON 3-27-04 MHF TANK TRAILER T-875 ARRIVED FOR OFF-LOADING.  AFTER PRESSURE WAS APPLIED INTERNALLY TO OFF LOAD INTO THE CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK A LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE REAR BOTTOM, APPROXIMATELY 16" IN FRONT OF THE SUMP. HONEYWELL'S DRIVERS STOPPED THE UNLOADING PROCESS IMMEDIATELY AFTER FINDING THE LEAKAGE.  AT THIS POINT THE HONEYWELL DRIVER'S PINPOINTED THE LEAKAGE AREA AND WERE ASKED TO MOVE AWAY FROM THE AREA BY EXXONMOBIL WHICH IN TURN TOOK OVER CONTROL OF THE LEAKING TRAILER.  HONEYWELL WAS THEN CONTACTED BY EXXONMOBIL FOR ASSISTANCE IN MITIGATING THE LEAK.  ALL HONEYWELL-GEISMAR CONCERNED PARTIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT INCLUDING PLANT MANAGEMENT, HSE, MAINTENANCE, AND LOGISTICS & DISTRIBUTION.  IN ADDITION, HF TECHNICAL SERVICE, THE INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTS BUSINESS GROUP AND HONEYWELL CHEMICALS MANAGEMENT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  FINALLY, HONEYWELL MADE A REQUEST TO EXXONMOBIL TO CONTACT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO REPORT THE LEAK.  TO EXPEDITE A SAFE CONCLUSION TO THIS INCIDENT, HONEYWELL (GEISMAR) REQUESTED THAT THE TRAILER BE ALLOWED TO CONTINUE OFF LOADING.  DURING THIS TIME PERIOD A WATER FOG WAS APPLIED TO TRAILER TO KNOCK DOWN THE MHF FUMES. AN AGREEMENT WAS REACHED BY BOTH PARTIES TO CONTINUE OFF LOADING. UNLOADING WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY HAVING THE HONEYWELL DRIVER'S RADIO THE EXXONMOBIL TECHNICIANS WITH EACH STEP REQUIRED TO UNLOAD.  FOLLOWING THE SUCCESSFUL OFF LOADING OF THE PRODUCT, EXXONMOBIL PULLED A VACUUM ON THE TRAILER TO REDUCE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE TO ZERO PSI.  A WATER FOG SPRAY WAS STILL POINTED AT THE LEAK AREA WHILE THE VACUUM WAS BEING PULLED.  ON 3-28-04 JAMES WATSON FROM HONEYWELL ARRIVED AT THE TORRANCE, EXXONMOBIL PLANT SITE TO INSPECT THE T 875.  A CONTACT POINT WAS SET UP WITH HONEYWELL BEFORE ENTERING THE PLANT WITH INFORMATION BEING RELAYED FROM BLAKE WISEMAN, JOHN MCCARTHY, BOB PRATT, AND JEFF LEESE.  IT WAS AGREED UPON TO USE JEFF LEESE AS THE MAIN CONTACT TO AVOID COMMUNICATION CONFUSION WHILE DEALING WITH THE ISSUE ON HAND.  JEFF SUPPLIED JAMES WITH CONTACT INSIDE THE PLANT (MITCH SCHIPIRO).  AFTER MEETING WITH MITCH AND PLANT PERSONNEL, MITCH STATED A NEED TO PLUG/PATCH THE LEAK TO PULL A BETTER MINUS.  A PLAN WAS DEVELOPED AND PUT IN PLACE TO SAFELY PLUG THE LEAK.  THE LEAK WAS SUCCESSFULLY STOPPED BY APPLYING A BELLY BAND TYPE OF STRAP PATCH.  ONCE THE PATCH WAS APPLIED THE MINUS PULLED DOWN GREATLY ALLOWING THE WATER FOG TO BE REMOVED WHICH REDUCED THE AMOUNT OF WATER RUN OFF AT THE LEAK SITE. ON 3-29-04, MONDAY MORNING MEETINGS WERE HELD BETWEEN TORRANCE, EXXONMOBIL, GEISMAR AND MORRISTOWN TO DISCUSS THE SAFE WATER WASH AND WATER DISCHARGE AT THE TORRANCE PLANT SITE.  JEFF LEESE PROVIDED WASHOUT PROCEDURES TO TORRANCE TO PROVIDE A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF WHAT WAS TO TAKE PLACE DURING WASHOUT.  TORRANCE AIDED HONEYWELL IN PROVIDING A (SWIMMING POOL) AREA TO OFF LOAD THE WASHOUT WATER.  EXXONMOBIL ALSO PROVIDED AN ASSORTMENT OF PIPEFITTINGS TO HOOK UP WASHOUT/UNLOADING PROCESS.  LATE MONDAY
THE TRACTOR TRAILER CAUGHT FIRE BECAUSE OF SOME DEFECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER, ALONG WITH THEIR CONTENTS, WERE DESTROYED.

FINALLY, HONEYWELL MADE A REQUEST TO EXXONMOBIL TO CONTACT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO REPORT THE LEAK.  TO EXPEDITE A SAFE CONCLUSION TO THIS INCIDENT, HONEYWELL (GEISMAR) REQUESTED THAT THE TRAILER BE ALLOWED TO CONTINUE OFF LOADING.  DURING THIS TIME PERIOD A WATER FOG WAS APPLIED TO TRAILER TO KNOCK DOWN THE MHF FUMES. AN AGREEMENT WAS REACHED BY BOTH PARTIES TO CONTINUE OFF LOADING. UNLOADING WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY HAVING THE HONEYWELL DRIVER'S RADIO THE EXXONMOBIL TECHNICIANS WITH EACH STEP REQUIRED TO UNLOAD.  FOLLOWING THE SUCCESSFUL OFF LOADING OF THE PRODUCT, EXXONMOBIL PULLED A VACUUM ON THE TRAILER TO REDUCE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE TO ZERO PSI.  A WATER FOG SPRAY WAS STILL POINTED AT THE LEAK AREA WHILE THE VACUUM WAS BEING PULLED.  ON 3-28-04 JAMES WATSON FROM HONEYWELL ARRIVED AT THE TORRANCE, EXXONMOBIL PLANT SITE TO INSPECT THE T 875.  A CONTACT POINT WAS SET UP WITH HONEYWELL BEFORE ENTERING THE PLANT WITH INFORMATION BEING RELAYED FROM BLAKE WISEMAN, JOHN MCCARTHY, BOB PRATT, AND JEFF LEESE.  IT WAS AGREED UPON TO USE JEFF LEESE AS THE MAIN CONTACT TO AVOID COMMUNICATION CONFUSION WHILE DEALING WITH THE ISSUE ON HAND.  JEFF SUPPLIED JAMES WITH CONTACT INSIDE THE PLANT (MITCH SCHIPIRO).  AFTER MEETING WITH MITCH AND PLANT PERSONNEL, MITCH STATED A NEED TO PLUG/PATCH THE LEAK TO PULL A BETTER MINUS.  A PLAN WAS DEVELOPED AND PUT IN PLACE TO SAFELY PLUG THE LEAK.  THE LEAK WAS SUCCESSFULLY STOPPED BY APPLYING A BELLY BAND TYPE OF STRAP PATCH.  ONCE THE PATCH WAS APPLIED THE MINUS PULLED DOWN GREATLY ALLOWING THE WATER FOG TO BE REMOVED WHICH REDUCED THE AMOUNT OF WATER RUN OFF AT THE LEAK SITE.

DRIVER PULLED UP TO WRONG LOCATION.  STARTED DELIVERY AND STOPPED AT 1.50 GALLONS AFTER NOT HEARING VENT ALARM.  DRIVER LOOKED IN WINDOW OF DWELLING SAW THE PIPES WERE NOT HOOKED TO TANK.  TANK HAD BEEN REMOVED BUT FILL PIPE WAS NOT.
